            "I'm trying to SSH into my Google Cloud VM from a Windows laptop, but I keep getting a public key error. How can I resolve this?\n",
            "Based on the search results, the most common issue for a **public key error** when SSH'ing into a Google Cloud VM from a Windows laptop is related to **username mismatches** or **incorrect SSH key configuration**. Here’s how to resolve it:\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **1. Check the Username in Your SSH Key**\n",
            "The error often occurs because the username in your SSH key does not match the username configured in the Google Cloud Console for your VM.\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Steps to Fix:\n",
            "1. **Locate Your SSH Key:**\n",
            "   - Open the SSH key file (e.g., `id_rsa.pub` or `gcp.pub`) and check the username at the end of the key.\n",
            "     Example:\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "     ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc2EAAA... user@host\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "     Here, `user` is the username embedded in the key.\n",
            "\n",
            "2. **Compare with Google Cloud Console:**\n",
            "   - Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/).\n",
            "   - Navigate to **Compute Engine > VM Instances**.\n",
            "   - Click on your VM instance and check the **SSH Keys** section.\n",
            "   - Ensure the username in the SSH key matches the username you’re using to log in.\n",
            "\n",
            "3. **Update the SSH Key:**\n",
            "   - If the usernames don’t match, regenerate the SSH key with the correct username:\n",
            "     ```bash\n",
            "     ssh-keygen -t rsa -f ~/.ssh/gcp -C \"your_google_account_username\"\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "   - Add the new key to your VM:\n",
            "     - Copy the contents of `~/.ssh/gcp.pub`.\n",
            "     - In the Google Cloud Console, paste it under **VM Instances > [Your VM] > SSH Keys**.\n",
            "\n",
            "4. **Update Your SSH Config File:**\n",
            "   - Open or create the SSH config file at `~/.ssh/config` and ensure the `User` field matches the username in your SSH key:\n",
            "     ```plaintext\n",
            "     Host my-vm\n",
            "       HostName [VM_EXTERNAL_IP]\n",
            "       User your_google_account_username\n",
            "       IdentityFile ~/.ssh/gcp\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **2. Ensure Correct Permissions for SSH Keys**\n",
            "Windows sometimes has issues with file permissions for SSH keys.\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Steps to Fix:\n",
            "1. **Navigate to Your `.ssh` Folder:**\n",
            "   - Open File Explorer and go to:\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "     C:\\Users\\<your_username>\\.ssh\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "\n",
            "2. **Set Correct Permissions:**\n",
            "   - Right-click the private key file (e.g., `gcp` or `id_rsa`).\n",
            "   - Go to **Properties > Security**.\n",
            "   - Ensure your user account has **Full Control** over the file.\n",
            "\n",
            "3. **Update the SSH Config File:**\n",
            "   - In your SSH config file (`~/.ssh/config`), use the **Windows-style path** for the `IdentityFile`:\n",
            "     ```plaintext\n",
            "     Host my-vm\n",
            "       HostName [VM_EXTERNAL_IP]\n",
            "       User your_google_account_username\n",
            "       IdentityFile C:\\Users\\<your_username>\\.ssh\\gcp\n",
            "     ```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **3. Use the Correct SSH Command**\n",
            "When connecting, use the correct syntax:\n",
            "```bash\n",
            "ssh -i ~/.ssh/gcp your_google_account_username@[VM_EXTERNAL_IP]\n",
            "```\n",
            "Or, if using the config file:\n",
            "```bash\n",
            "ssh my-vm\n",
            "```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **4. Temporary Workaround**\n",
            "If you still face issues, you can use the **Google Cloud Console’s built-in SSH** feature:\n",
            "1. Go to [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/).\n",
            "2. Navigate to **Compute Engine > VM Instances**.\n",
            "3. Click **SSH** next to your VM instance.\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **References**\n",
            "- [GCP: SSH public key error - multiple users / usernames](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/module-1/102_eb759226aa_gcp-ssh-public-key-error-multiple-users-usernames.md)\n",
            "- [SSH error in VS Code - “Could not establish connection to \"de-zoomcamp\": Permission denied (publickey).”](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/module-2/001_7889d2bad5_ssh-error-in-vs-code-could-not-establish-connectio.md)\n",
            "\n",
            "I'm encountering a `UnicodeDecodeError` when reading a CSV file in Python. How can I fix this issue?\n",
            "To resolve a `UnicodeDecodeError` when reading a CSV file in Python, you can try the following solutions:\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **1. Specify the Correct Encoding**\n",
            "The most common cause of this error is that the file is not encoded in UTF-8. You can try specifying a different encoding when reading the file. Common encodings include:\n",
            "- `latin1` (also known as `iso-8859-1`)\n",
            "- `cp1252` (Windows-1252)\n",
            "- `utf-16`\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Example:\n",
            "```python\n",
            "import pandas as pd\n",
            "\n",
            "# Try reading with a different encoding\n",
            "df = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding='latin1', low_memory=False)\n",
            "```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **2. Use `errors='replace'` or `errors='ignore'`**\n",
            "If you're unsure about the encoding, you can use the `errors` parameter to handle problematic characters:\n",
            "- `errors='replace'`: Replaces invalid characters with a placeholder (e.g., `�`).\n",
            "- `errors='ignore'`: Skips invalid characters entirely.\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Example:\n",
            "```python\n",
            "df = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding='utf-8', errors='replace')\n",
            "```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **3. Detect the Encoding Automatically**\n",
            "You can use libraries like `chardet` to detect the file's encoding before reading it.\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Example:\n",
            "```python\n",
            "import chardet\n",
            "\n",
            "# Detect the encoding\n",
            "with open('your_file.csv', 'rb') as f:\n",
            "    result = chardet.detect(f.read())\n",
            "\n",
            "# Read the file with the detected encoding\n",
            "df = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding=result['encoding'])\n",
            "```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **4. Use `pd.read_csv` with `engine='python'`**\n",
            "Sometimes, using the Python engine instead of the C engine can help avoid encoding issues.\n",
            "\n",
            "#### Example:\n",
            "```python\n",
            "df = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', engine='python')\n",
            "```\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **5. Convert the File to UTF-8**\n",
            "If possible, open the file in a text editor (e.g., Notepad++, VS Code) and save it with UTF-8 encoding. Then, try reading it again.\n",
            "\n",
            "---\n",
            "\n",
            "### **Reference**\n",
            "The solutions above are based on common practices for handling encoding issues in Python. For more details, you can refer to the following resource:\n",
            "- [Python: Invalid Start Byte Error Message](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/module-3/041_55b6d6256f_python-invalid-start-byte-error-message.md)\n",
            "\n"
          ]
        }
