              "type": "dataframe",
              "variable_name": "df_evals",
              "summary": "{\n  \"name\": \"df_evals\",\n  \"rows\": 10,\n  \"fields\": [\n    {\n      \"column\": \"file\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"faq_agent_v2_20260402_121040_6d4390.json\",\n          \"faq_agent_v2_20260402_121045_47f89d.json\",\n          \"faq_agent_v2_20260402_121127_7db0c0.json\"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"question\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"How can I retrieve the DDL statement for a BigQuery table to recreate its schema and data layout?\",\n          \"I missed the registration deadline for the course. Can I still submit the homework and final project?\",\n          \"I'm encountering a `UnicodeDecodeError` when reading a CSV file in Python. How can I fix this issue?\"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"answer\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"To retrieve the **DDL (Data Definition Language)** statement for a BigQuery table and recreate its schema and data layout, you can use the **`INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES`** view. This method works for both **native (managed) tables** and **external tables**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **Steps to Retrieve DDL for a BigQuery Table**\\n\\n#### **1. For Native (Managed) Tables**\\nRun the following query, replacing `your_dataset` and `your_table_name` with your dataset and table names:\\n\\n```sql\\nSELECT table_name, ddl\\nFROM `your_dataset`.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES\\nWHERE table_name = 'your_table_name';\\n```\\n\\n**Example:**\\n```sql\\nSELECT table_name, ddl\\nFROM `zoomcamp.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES`\\nWHERE table_name = 'yellow_tripdata_parquet';\\n```\\n\\nThis will return the `CREATE TABLE` statement required to recreate the table, including all columns, data types, and constraints.\\n\\n---\\n\\n#### **2. For External Tables**\\nThe process is the same, but the DDL will include the `OPTIONS` clause specifying the external data source (e.g., format and file URIs).\\n\\n**Example:**\\n```sql\\nSELECT table_name, ddl\\nFROM `zoomcamp.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES`\\nWHERE table_name = 'yellow_tripdata_parquet_ext';\\n```\\n\\nThe result will look like:\\n```sql\\nCREATE EXTERNAL TABLE `zoomcamp-ingenieria-datos.zoomcamp.yellow_tripdata_parquet_ext`\\nOPTIONS(\\n    format=\\\"PARQUET\\\",\\n    uris=[\\\"gs://newyork-taxi/yellow_tripdata_*.parquet\\\"]\\n);\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **Key Notes**\\n- This method works for both **native** and **external** tables.\\n- The `ddl` column in the `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES` view contains the full `CREATE TABLE` or `CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE` statement.\\n- For more details, refer to the [BigQuery `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES` documentation](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/information-schema-tables).\\n\\n---\\n**Reference:**\\n[How to obtain the DDL of a table in BigQuery?](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/module-3/025_7df3102580_bigquery-table-ddl-information-schema.md)\",\n          \"Based on the available information, here's what applies to your situation:\\n\\n1. **Late Homework Submissions**:\\n   Late submissions for homework are **not allowed**. If the submission form is still open after the due date, you *may* still submit, but it will be considered late. Always confirm your submission by checking the date-timestamp on the course page while logged in.\\n   [(Source)](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/general/017_4dbd2eea47_homework-are-late-submissions-of-homework-allowed.md)\\n\\n2. **Project Submissions**:\\n   - You have **two attempts** to submit your project.\\n   - If you miss the first project deadline, you can still submit during the second attempt.\\n   - The second attempt is also available if you fail the first submission.\\n   [(Source)](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/general/039_9b0561dbf8_project-what-is-project-attempt-1-and-project-atte.md)\\n   [(Source)](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/project/004_5c5321c295_project-1-project-2.md)\\n\\n### Summary:\\n- **Homework**: Late submissions are generally not allowed, but you can submit if the form is still open (though it may be considered late).\\n- **Final Project**: You can submit during the second attempt if you miss the first deadline.\\n\\nFor exact dates and further clarification, check the [course website](https://courses.datatalks.club/de-zoomcamp-2025/) or the [Google Calendar](https://calendar.google.com/calendar/?cid=ZXIxcjA1M3ZlYjJpcXU0dTFmaG02MzVxMG9AZ3JvdXAuY2FsZW5kYXIuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbQ).\\n[(Source)](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/general/016_d3f485cd10_homework-what-are-homework-and-project-deadlines.md)\",\n          \"To resolve a `UnicodeDecodeError` when reading a CSV file in Python, you can try the following solutions:\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **1. Specify the Correct Encoding**\\nThe most common cause of this error is that the file is not encoded in UTF-8. You can try specifying a different encoding when reading the file. Common encodings include:\\n- `latin1` (also known as `iso-8859-1`)\\n- `cp1252` (Windows-1252)\\n- `utf-16`\\n\\n#### Example:\\n```python\\nimport pandas as pd\\n\\n# Try reading with a different encoding\\ndf = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding='latin1', low_memory=False)\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **2. Use `errors='replace'` or `errors='ignore'`**\\nIf you're unsure about the encoding, you can use the `errors` parameter to handle problematic characters:\\n- `errors='replace'`: Replaces invalid characters with a placeholder (e.g., `\\ufffd`).\\n- `errors='ignore'`: Skips invalid characters entirely.\\n\\n#### Example:\\n```python\\ndf = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding='utf-8', errors='replace')\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **3. Detect the Encoding Automatically**\\nYou can use libraries like `chardet` to detect the file's encoding before reading it.\\n\\n#### Example:\\n```python\\nimport chardet\\n\\n# Detect the encoding\\nwith open('your_file.csv', 'rb') as f:\\n    result = chardet.detect(f.read())\\n\\n# Read the file with the detected encoding\\ndf = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', encoding=result['encoding'])\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **4. Use `pd.read_csv` with `engine='python'`**\\nSometimes, using the Python engine instead of the C engine can help avoid encoding issues.\\n\\n#### Example:\\n```python\\ndf = pd.read_csv('your_file.csv', engine='python')\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **5. Convert the File to UTF-8**\\nIf possible, open the file in a text editor (e.g., Notepad++, VS Code) and save it with UTF-8 encoding. Then, try reading it again.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **Reference**\\nThe solutions above are based on common practices for handling encoding issues in Python. For more details, you can refer to the following resource:\\n- [Python: Invalid Start Byte Error Message](https://github.com/DataTalksClub/faq/blob/main/_questions/data-engineering-zoomcamp/module-3/041_55b6d6256f_python-invalid-start-byte-error-message.md)\"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"instructions_follow\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"instructions_avoid\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"answer_relevant\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"answer_clear\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"answer_citations\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 2,\n        \"samples\": [\n          false\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"completeness\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"tool_call_search\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"boolean\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 1,\n        \"samples\": [\n          true\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}"
